			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ah again the definition of a casual player yet again, but consider this variable.
<br />

<br />
Playing EQ is much like life, you expect (in each persons mind) certain things to remain the same.  For example, your parents you expect them to be around forever (if you have them) so,
<br />

<br />
Your age 18, Parents are 38.
<br />
Your age 28, Parents are 48.
<br />
Your age 38, Parents are 58.
<br />

<br />
Relative progression.
<br />

<br />
So, whats my point?
<br />

<br />
EQ has been around for 5 years, all the old timers have spent a pretty good chunk of their lives in EQ.
<br />

<br />
You are changing as much as EQ is changing.
<br />

<br />
Consider a player starting EQ 5 years ago at:
<br />

<br />
Age 14, now 19 (going to college or staring to work)
<br />
Age 19, now 24 (close to or finishing college or very much into work)
<br />
Age 24, now 29 (possibly married or considering having a family or at least being married)
<br />
Age 29, now 34 (possibly married and thinking or considering saving for a housewhatever)
<br />

<br />
Anyhow you get the picture, Real Life move on as you play this game.
<br />

<br />
Thats why youll see sooo many posts saying that they were once raiders and now casual.
<br />

<br />
There is NO way you can Raid or LDoN often and be married, if you are doing that, you ARE an exception.
<br />

<br />
Disclaimer: please dont say all your friends in EQ are that way, because thats like saying that everyone in my Alcoholics Anonymous thinks and does as you do (Im not in AA BTW).
<br />

<br />
But, what if you started casual, they spent the same money, understand the limitations of a casual player within EQ, you DO realize that many options and equipment are simply denied (and for most casual players, they understand that).
<br />

<br />
Even as the previous poster said, even 1000 AP is enormous to a true casual player, you have to find a group, preferably to an LDoN adventure that would benefit you, assemble the group with all the key members (or close to it), then you still have to WIN (which you still might fail, that means net ZERO).
<br />

<br />
With declining player numbers, it is getting very difficult to create groups again, equating to more time need to even start let alone finishing an adventure.
<br />

<br />
So, all the people who DO have a lot of time to play, please do NOT feel threatened, true casuals will not even come close, big deal they have one item that closely rivals yours, you will be long gone to higher and bigger targets and better NO DROP loot.
<br />

<br />
The players who can spend a lot of time in EQ do not realize that if all these casuals starts to drop off, then your content will suffer too and no one will buy your 2 year old Leet droppable loot from you for 20K plat.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, I used to believe that as a casual player, we do not deserve anything, but seeing how all these ubers dropping out and moving onum, guess whos left to fill the void??
<br />

<br />
Anyway food for thought.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
