				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There is NO way you can Raid or LDoN often and be married, if you are doing that, you ARE an exception. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is not at all true.  This is the type of blanket statement that normally ends up getting people who raid upset.
<br />

<br />
First, there are many married people in my raiding guild - myself included.  Raiding is no worse than watching TV - and for many takes about the same amount of time.  You are talking about 4-6 hours a night.  The average household with Cable spends about 61 hours a week watching television - I spend far less than that raiding.
<br />

<br />
I'm married - I go out with my wife once a week, I go to movies twice a month, my school/work (they just happen to be the same thing for me) take between 8-10 hours a day.  Even with that, sleeping 7 hours a day, 2 hours for transport to and from and getting ready I can still spend a couple hours with my wife each day talking and whatnot before I go to sleep and raid 4 hours a day.
<br />

<br />
EQ - like anything else in life - is only as detrimental as you allow it to be- regardless of what other things you have to do.  There are many raiding guilds that do not raid every day.  Take Harmonium as an example (not my guild, Lifebane's - I figure since he has been a member of this community for much longer than most some might actually listen to him) - they used to raid 3 or 4 days a week - and I believe they still do.  Even when a guild raids 6 nights a week (which tends to be the extreme) - there is no rule that you cannot take a night off now and again.
<br />

<br />
Rather than make an assumption that is entirely unsupportable - why not go and try to talk to a few of your server's top raiding guilds members.  Find out how many of them are older than 23 - people who have finished or are finishing college, who have their own jobs and families but who have traded TV time for game time.  It is my experience that these people still put their families and jobs first - just they've managed to learn that a bit of scheduling can make things go a lot easier.<br />_________________<br />Xalion Buscador 
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=455682" target="_blank" class="postlink">My junk</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
